https://w3id.org/babelon/source_value.value: An atrial arrhythmia characterized by disorganized atrial activity without discrete P waves on the surface EKG, but instead by an undulating baseline or more sharply circumscribed atrial deflections of varying amplitude an frequency ranging from 350 to 600 per minute.

definition.value: The ventricular response to atrial fibrillation is irregularly irregular because of the large number of atrial impulses that transit the atrioventricular node, making the ventricle partially refractory to further impulses. Atrial fibrillation can cause a number of manifestations including excessive ventricular response with angina pectoris or hypotension in susceptible individuals, syncope, systemic embolization, fatigue, or anxiety. These features should be coded separately.

https://w3id.org/babelon/source_value.value: Subvalvular stenosis is caused by a diaphragm-like membrane. The stenosis is clinically manifested like any other form of aortic stenosis but is often associated with some aortic insufficiency.

definition.value: An important feature in the differential diagnosis between valvular and subvalvular aortic stenosis is the fact that no ejection sound is present in the latter.

https://w3id.org/babelon/comment.value: label of HP:0005184 (Prolonged QTc interval)  ; abnormality of the cardiovascular system
preview
preview

https://w3id.org/babelon/source_value.value: A longer than normal interval (corrected for heart rate) between the Q and T waves in the heart's cycle. Prolonged QTc can cause premature action potentials during late phase depolarizations thereby leading to ventricular arrhythmias and ventricular fibrillations.

https://w3id.org/babelon/comment.value: label of HP:0005185 (Global systolic dysfunction)  ; abnormality of the cardiovascular system

value.value: 全身性収縮期機能障害
